1558","1565":"1565","about 1537":"circa 1537","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","6 October 1515":"6 oktober 1515","about 1565":"circa 1565","Abt. 1540":"1540","2 November 1565":"2 november 1565","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1504":"1504","1515":"1515","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England":"Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northampton,England":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"6 October 1515–2 November 1565":"6 October 1515–2 November 1565","1515–1565":"1515–1565","1550–Female":"1550–Deceased","1519–1564":"1519–1564","1538–Female":"1538–Deceased","1540–1585":"1540–1585","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1480–1565":"1480–1565","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","Abt 1538":"about 1538","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","about 1537":"about 1537","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","6 October 1515":"6 October 1515","about 1565":"about 1565","Abt. 1540":"1540","2 November 1565":"2 November 1565","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1504":"1504","1515":"1515","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England":"Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Northampton,England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"WARD","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a watchman or guard, from Middle English <i>ward</i> ‘watchman, guard’ (Old English <i>weard</i>, used as both an agent noun and an abstract noun).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>warde</i> ‘armed guard’ (Old English <i>weard</i> ‘watching, guarding’), with the same meaning as 1 above.","Irish: shortened form of <b>McWard</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhaird</b> ‘son of the poet’. The surname occurs throughout Ireland, where three different branches of the family are known as professional poets."],"variants":[{"name":"Warshawsky","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Ari, Hyman.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from the city of Warsaw (Polish <i>Warszawa</i>), which became the capital of Poland at the end of the 16th century, after the destruction of Kraków by fire.","Americanized form of Polish <b>Warszawski</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Wardman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>wardman</i>, either in the general sense ‘watchman, guard’ (compare   Ward  ) or in the administrative sense ‘representative of a ward within a borough’."]},{"name":"Warde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Donal.","Irish: variant of   Ward  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":33,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":42,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas WARD was born on 6 October 1515, in Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England, his father, John Ward, was 36 and his mother, Elizabeth Hancock, was 35. He married Emma Hare Parnell about 1537, in Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 2 November 1565, in his hometown, at the age of 50, and was buried in Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"6 October 1515–2 November 1565":"6. oktoober 1515–2. november 1565","1515–1565":"1515–1565","1550–Female":"1550–Surnud","1519–1564":"1519–1564","1538–Female":"1538–Surnud","1540–1585":"1540–1585","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1480–1565":"1480–1565","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","Abt 1538":"umbes 1538","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","about 1537":"umbes 1537","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","6 October 1515":"6. oktoober 1515","about 1565":"umbes 1565","Abt. 1540":"1540","2 November 1565":"2. november 1565","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1504":"1504","1515":"1515","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England":"Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northampton,England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"6 October 1515–2 November 1565":"6. lokakuuta 1515–2. marraskuuta 1565","1515–1565":"1515–1565","1550–Female":"1550–Kuollut","1519–1564":"1519–1564","1538–Female":"1538–Kuollut","1540–1585":"1540–1585","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1480–1565":"1480–1565","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","Abt 1538":"noin 1538","1558":"1558","1565":"1565","about 1537":"noin 1537","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","6 October 1515":"6. lokakuuta 1515","about 1565":"noin 1565","Abt. 1540":"1540","2 November 1565":"2. marraskuuta 1565","1519":"1519